snippet.textDisplay:
First things first: congrats.
To you, for having the chance to do such a great gift to your dad. You worked hard, you had success but... it's still sometimes matter of luck. And you earned it.
And to your dad, for having such a huge fan as you, and for have a little dream on 4 wheels. I hope he's enjoying it.
Now, hints and ideas...
Disclaimer: i did not read any of over 30 thousands comments, too long. I'm not expecting that you'll read mine, so if i am writing something already said, my bad, was not intentional.
-Putting back drain plug/cap before loosen the filter was not the better idea. When the filter is loose, some of the oil contained into the oil pump to the filter was released into the sump pan. If the drain plug were still lose, could also run out from the engine, and do a "bit better" oil change. The "best" solution should be IMVHO:
-loosen drain plug
-wait the oil drop
-loosen the filter ap
-wait until the end of the oil drops out
-snug the drain plug back
-pour a bit of fresh oil into filter housing until you can see it into the housing
-put back the new filter on the housing and snug it
-re-assemble air filter
-pour the remaining oil into the engine
In this way, the oil line from the pump to the filter should be filled a bit more with fresh oil into the first crank, helping to reduce wear due to lack of lubricant. It's also far more time consuming and fresher as look. And also might sound a bit... D.O.C. but it's just an idea :)
-oil selection: as far as i know, the V6 was made into Ferrari plant exclusively for Maserati, but it's not an "original project", should be based on Pentastar V6 engine layout. Model Year 2014 for 3.0 S gasoline AWD sold in europe says SAE 5W40, API SL/CF and ACEA A3. ACEA is a european oil specs set created by constructor's association and... "means something". If you can, consider to choose an oil complying with this specification.
-oil change interval: still referring to MY2014 for europe, oil change is due every two years and/or 20k KM (12.5k Miles), which one came first. Please do not trust two year interval, if your dad drives less than 15.000 miles a year, change the oil every year. Do not let the oil "die" for high temperatures into the engine and spread as sludge into the engine. I think that your dad is a car-wise gentleman, who asks power only when the engine is warm, but anyway long oil change interval made by car maker are often choosen to lower environment impact of the single car, lowering the costs for the car maker. It's anyway a powerful engine, so oil shape is vital to keep a long life for that.

Hope that these hints will be interesting for you and the new drive for your dad. Enjoy, and take care.

snippet.textDisplay: Chris in order to do a proper oil change you need to remove or at least fully loosen the oil filer before draining the oil. On every car there is an return valve which holds oil in filter for the pressure not too drop after car been parked. Basically what you have done is pour all of the oil from filter back into the sump. Not an issue but really you should try to get as much oil out as possible especially the one that is just before the filter ;)
